WEBVTT

00:03.372 --> 00:06.395
There's always that. In any organization, you 
have that problem. But anyway, you wanted to go

00:09.298 --> 00:15.003
back to the origination of what the conference 
was. How about your getting up to Texas A&M, if you

00:15.023 --> 00:17.085
don't mind? How did that happen? Well, I'll tell 
you how it happened. My mother wanted me to become a

00:22.130 --> 00:24.072
doctor. So my mother died early. But anyway, I had 
planned on going to Rice. So I was there. Accepted

00:32.735 --> 00:33.616
at Rice. But that summer, I went over to Louisiana 
to work in oil fields. Where did you work in

00:39.626 --> 00:40.948
Louisiana? I worked in Vinton, Louisiana, in some 
little wells my brother had, Johnny had. And then I

00:46.557 --> 00:50.243
decided I wanted to become a program engineering 
geologist. So then I changed. Instead of going to

00:51.766 --> 00:54.490
Rice, I registered at A&M. and started to take a 
program in engineering and geology. And that's

00:57.142 --> 00:58.564
how I came to A&M. Had the brother been there or 
anyone in the family at all? Johnny was a graduate

01:00.506 --> 01:02.948
of A&M and so was my older brother. He had gone for a 
year and then went over to Texas. And Johnny was a

01:05.731 --> 01:08.855
chemical engineer graduate of A&M. He was about 
seven years my senior. He worked for Exxon. Then he

01:11.898 --> 01:14.881
was out busy drilling a few little wells, working 
over wells. He left Exxon by the time I was a senior

01:14.901 --> 01:18.345
in high school. And that summer before school 
started, the university started, and I went

01:19.005 --> 01:23.110
there. I'd gone back to... to my school at 
Galveston, even after I graduated a year because I

01:24.878 --> 01:37.919
was too young, too small, and I had to take a third 
year of Latin to be able to qualify for taking

01:24.878 --> 01:37.919
pre-med or whatever to go to Rice. So I went back. 
But I was now taking also trigonometry and solid

01:39.041 --> 01:42.627
geometry. So I did so well in those, I decided I'd be 
an engineer and geologist when I decided to get

01:42.647 --> 01:48.256
into oil and gas. Brother did straight geology. 
Did you ride the train up to College Station, or how

01:49.870 --> 01:53.033
did you go? Yeah, I rode the train when I went to 
College Station, and I may have heard it because

01:53.053 --> 02:09.591
when I talked to the, I think to one of the 
graduation things at A&M, I'd mentioned that when

01:53.053 --> 02:09.591
I got off the train, because my aunt put me on the 
train in Houston. She drove up from Galveston, put

02:09.832 --> 02:11.533
me on the train. I drove up, and I had to get off all 
alone, 16-year-old kid, Walking across the

02:16.263 --> 02:18.366
campus, wondering what the hell was going to 
happen. It was a long walk, huh? A long walk. Up that

02:20.189 --> 02:20.449
hill. You know, from the old train station over to 
campus there. But it was a very nostalgic memory.

02:25.136 --> 02:26.778
But anyway, A&M was a great school. And, you know, 
for $450 a year, I could go to school in a room and

02:27.018 --> 02:31.164
board and everything. And it was tough. And my 
father didn't have any money. I'd have to do some

02:33.908 --> 02:36.392
work in the mess hall. And I built bookshelves. And 
I was cleaning and pressing laundry. And I had a

02:41.119 --> 02:45.645
candy concession where the damn football players 
would steal all the time and not pay me. And then I

02:46.638 --> 02:51.623
did, it was tough the first couple of years, but I 
managed to get by. And the last year, I made money. I

02:53.966 --> 02:57.290
made more money when I graduated than I got from 
Amical when I went to work for them. I developed, I

02:58.391 --> 03:07.841
was the one who originated the stationery that had 
its beautiful gold and embossed field artillery

02:58.391 --> 03:07.841
and signal corps. I originated that. In fact, 
there's some sheets of that in the archives. It

03:10.344 --> 03:13.708
used to be just plain print, maroon print on the 
white paper. So I got a San Antonio printer. who

03:16.304 --> 03:19.527
developed that for me, and then I had an agent in 
every dormitory. And I was making $300 a month when

03:19.887 --> 03:25.152
I got it from school, and I only took a $126 salary at 
A&M University. I mean, at Amical University,

03:25.292 --> 03:28.775
Amical, in South Louisiana. So I took a cut in 
salary to leave A&M. But that, I wanted to take

03:32.619 --> 03:35.922
engineering, and I didn't want to go in the Army. I 
knew the war was coming on. We all knew that, but I

03:38.705 --> 03:41.988
wanted to get some experience. So what I decided, 
even though I was offered a full commission

03:42.008 --> 03:45.771
because... I had excellent grades, and I was in 
battalion command and everything at A&M, but I

03:46.240 --> 03:52.428
didn't want to get in the service. The war hadn't 
come on. But I was a reserve officer, and then when I

03:54.831 --> 04:02.301
was in South Louisiana, I think it was September 
before the war, they called me to active duty. I

04:03.643 --> 04:12.214
went with the Corps of Engineers, and I did all 
construction on Dixon Gun Plant, Sergeant Ernest

04:03.643 --> 04:12.214
Depot, all these airfields around Texas here. 
with the Corps of Engineers. So I got tremendous

04:14.314 --> 04:15.876
experience. I ended up first lieutenant, 
supervising 150 people. And you were mainly

04:20.641 --> 04:22.083
involved in construction. Mainly engineering 
and construction. Engineering officer, what I

04:24.806 --> 04:26.888
was, assistant engineering officer. And 
therefore, I got great experience. And then when

04:30.092 --> 04:33.576
the war ended, I lost four and a half years. So I just 
came to Houston and decided, to hell with it. I lost

04:36.640 --> 04:42.066
all my contemporaries that stayed with the 
company for some reason or other because of being

04:42.670 --> 04:44.032
classified as 4F. They had come up, and they ranked 
pretty well in the company. And the company

04:46.937 --> 04:50.502
offered me a job, because they thought I was a good 
engineering geologist. And I had been involved in

04:51.363 --> 04:55.610
South Louisiana, which was a tremendous field for 
Amaco. It was called Stanley in the old days,

04:55.630 --> 04:57.974
Stanley Oil and Gas. And they had a tremendous 
operation there. And I had a lot of experience in

05:01.199 --> 05:04.003
the year and a half that I was down. So therefore, I 
came to Houston and said, this is where I want to set

05:04.895 --> 05:08.119
up and become a consultant. Were you in 
production, primarily, or exploration? I was in

05:09.902 --> 05:12.505
exploration, geology, and production. They had 
exploitation engineers, you see. And we did all

05:15.249 --> 05:17.051
the exploitation. And we didn't do the basic 
regional geology. We did the exploitation

05:24.000 --> 05:27.585
geology and engineering, too. So I did both, 
because my background was both. And therefore,

05:30.649 --> 05:33.012
when I came to Houston, My brother had come here 
also, and he had some friends. And I was able to get

05:36.268 --> 05:44.275
six people to fund me $50 each with a little 
override to see if I could find oil and gas for them.

05:44.395 --> 05:45.416
And that was it. And I would do the deals. I'd do the 
geology and engineering, and then I'd get my

05:49.600 --> 05:52.963
brother and my partner. That's all we had, one girl 
in the office with us. They'd go down to Esperson

05:55.425 --> 05:58.708
Drugstore and sell the deals. Were you doing any 
seismograph work, or how were you doing? No, I

06:01.751 --> 06:03.893
would do subsurface geology. In fact, when it 
first started, we had so little money. None of you

06:08.001 --> 06:09.303
may have heard this before. I had a friend called 
John Todd who had a Cambie blueprint, and I

06:10.204 --> 06:14.448
couldn't afford to buy the logs. So I'd borrow the 
logs at 6 o'clock. I'd work about 3 in the morning,

06:19.594 --> 06:22.678
and I'd bring them back for 8 o'clock. He wouldn't 
charge me. And I'd do some of my geology to start

06:23.959 --> 06:26.202
with, you see. So that's the way. And then we would 
get people at Bacchus for 32nd overriding

06:27.475 --> 06:31.259
interest. Eventually, we'd get more. And 
eventually, we'd get a quarter in that front. We'd

06:34.643 --> 06:36.605
get big people like Bob Smith. And we had all the 
Jewish people in town taking deals for us called

06:36.625 --> 06:40.770
the Big Nine. Oh, they were good, too. Wine 
Gardens, all the Jewish people that you know, the

06:42.672 --> 06:47.678
Battlesteins, they're all to Oshkosh. And you 
were working this area primarily? We were working

06:49.260 --> 06:51.703
the Gulf Coast region here. Except that we did work 
some areas, just like our North Texas prospect

06:51.723 --> 06:56.188
came to us from a Chicago bookie, believe it or not, 
through one of my partners. That's a hell of a story

07:01.228 --> 07:03.591
in itself. But he asked me to check, and I said, 
hell, what the hell does a Chicago bookie know

07:03.611 --> 07:09.159
about Texas Auto and Gas? He just had a deal, and I 
found out it came to him through one of my friends

07:09.899 --> 07:15.106
been trying to sell it, named Allison Miles. I 
didn't know him, but he had gone to A&M. Had been

07:18.190 --> 07:19.892
trying for two years to sell the deal. He couldn't 
sell it to the Chicago bookie. He wanted to know if

07:21.695 --> 07:23.577
we'd look at it. One of my participants called him, 
General Pulaski. He wasn't a general, but they

07:26.076 --> 07:27.298
called him that. He said, come on, you've got to 
look at this deal. I said, well, all right,

07:29.261 --> 07:30.423
General, I'll look at it. And that's where we made 
one of the big discoveries on the Texas. So you

07:33.088 --> 07:34.250
never know. No, you don't. But anyway. Did you ever 
read that book about Petillo Higgins? No, I

07:40.159 --> 07:41.922
haven't seen that book there. I haven't read that 
one. It's quite a story. Did you ever know him? No, I

07:45.528 --> 07:47.151
know of him, but I don't know him. Do you have the 
book? David Norton was going to give it to you. I

07:50.184 --> 07:51.005
think I have the book. I think you really enjoyed 
that. Higgins did a great job on Spinal Tap.

07:54.830 --> 07:55.691
There's no question. Quite an adventurer. Well, 
oil and gas are that way. A lot of these people are

07:58.014 --> 07:59.256
that way. But the oil and gas was good. We began 
slowly, and we kept getting a little better and

08:01.499 --> 08:05.283
better interest in it. We found a lot of oil and gas. 
I did consulting work for Glenn McCarthy and a lot

08:06.305 --> 08:09.589
of other people. Eddie Scurll, I'm glad, the 
old-timers you've heard of. Floyd Carsten and

08:13.855 --> 08:17.239
them, besides creating our own company. I was 
doing both things. The consulting work, I'd do,

08:19.519 --> 08:23.224
and I'd sell deals to them, make a little override 
there. But we began to build our company. That's

08:25.027 --> 08:27.711
where we really started our company. So most of the 
oil and gas we had, we found most of it ourselves. So

08:30.495 --> 08:32.498
that's the difference where we're at than most 
companies. When did you organize? What was your

08:34.882 --> 08:37.886
first company organized as, or when did you do 
that? It was organized in 1946. That's when I came

08:39.489 --> 08:41.412
in January of 46. It was organized probably in June 
of 46. So you organized right away. You and I just

08:43.595 --> 08:44.276
consulted. It was organized as Rock Soil. And 
Rob's got some history on that. He's got some

08:48.340 --> 08:49.442
history on that. In 46, and they had three 
partners, and one guy named Jimmy Gray, after he

08:49.922 --> 08:58.853
was in about six months, I was getting a little 
overhyped for doing the work for them. He said, I

08:59.434 --> 09:01.677
got a third interest. I'm going to Oklahoma. I'm 
leaving. Do you want to buy it? So I got the

09:04.200 --> 09:07.403
gentleman to back my note for $9,000. And he had a 
little money in, so I bought him out for the third of

09:07.423 --> 09:12.730
this little fledgling company that just started. 
I think we had one well at Kaplan and one well at

09:13.411 --> 09:16.234
North Kiran. So I bought my interest in it, and the 
general helped me bank it. He signed my note for me.

09:21.906 --> 09:22.847
So General Pulaski. But that's how I got in the 
company. Then, of course, we started building the

09:24.830 --> 09:26.432
company. In the meantime, I was also doing 
consulting work for a number of people around here

09:26.452 --> 09:34.021
that would pay me enough, because I had two kids 
here and one on the way. In other words, it's very,

09:35.523 --> 09:43.773
and I get that a little naive, to think that with a 
year and a half experience, I could become a

09:35.523 --> 09:43.773
consulting engineer and geologist. And that's 
what I did. That's what you really did, yeah. But I

09:47.112 --> 09:50.435
knew Houston was the place to be, so that's one 
thing I picked the right place to be. That's when

09:50.976 --> 09:53.739
things were taking over. There was a backlog of 
prospects that couldn't drill wells during the

09:53.759 --> 09:59.925
war because steel was unavailable. We were 
furnishing all our allies with all the oil that

09:59.945 --> 10:02.348
they had. And therefore, I knew that Houston was 
the place to be. Then when did you organize

10:09.595 --> 10:12.138
Mitchell Energy Development? Well, after the 
oil, rock soil, then we created a company called I

10:17.453 --> 10:23.378
think it's Christie, Mitchell, and Mitchell, 
which is a successor to Rock Soil. And that was the

10:24.139 --> 10:27.622
three partners, myself and my brother Johnny. 
They were older than I was. And myself. They would

10:29.944 --> 10:32.867
outsell the deals I'd do with the children in 
engineering. And we finally hired a couple of

10:32.887 --> 10:37.371
people to help us because we taught drilling 
wells, making a few wells. And I would say we

10:38.412 --> 10:47.140
organized that probably in the early 50 or 51, 
Christie, Mitchell, and Mitchell. And then we

10:48.082 --> 10:54.470
started making a lot of discoveries with Palacios 
and North Texas in 53. And we've discovered a lot of

10:54.550 --> 10:58.195
oil and gas reservoirs and fields. And then we 
changed it to George Mitchell Associates. And

11:04.262 --> 11:08.027
then in 72, we became Mitchell Engine Development 
when we went public. That's when I first met Joe.

11:10.169 --> 11:15.456
And when I went to Chicago to make presentations 
to, he's working with Hershey, Rodman, and Druck.

11:16.060 --> 11:20.426
to see if they thought that we could sell our 
product to the investment community. You know,

11:21.488 --> 11:23.892
whether they thought we had enough, whatever it 
was. And they thought, you know, they helped us get

11:24.573 --> 11:28.358
the information around the country. So that when 
we went public, the stock sold when it was sold. Oh,

11:33.205 --> 11:36.430
probably a third of the company, that's all that 
was sold down, more than that. And my brother, I had

11:37.171 --> 11:42.339
bought out most of his, and then I bought out my 
other partner before that. My brother had about

11:43.300 --> 11:45.223
20% of the company I had. more than that. And he 
eventually sold most of his and did other things.

11:50.282 --> 11:55.406
So then I ended up with most of the company, 
probably 63%. What was your first experience in

11:55.426 --> 11:57.388
real estate? Well, the first experience was very 
interesting. First experience was, I guess, back

12:01.812 --> 12:08.537
in 1961

12:01.812 --> 12:08.537
or two. Someone, a person in Galveston I knew named 
Spro, a woman, called me and said, I knew him in high

12:16.118 --> 12:28.181
school, George, that my husband who just died left 
some real estate to the Texas bank. We used to be in a

12:28.221 --> 12:33.672
Texas bank down here where the Chronicle building 
was.

12:46.004 --> 12:48.988
Some husband, wasn't it? Society for the 
Prevention of Frailty of Animals, yeah. She could

12:51.892 --> 12:57.661
get the income, but then the property would go to 
the dogs, so to speak. She said, they're getting

12:59.163 --> 13:04.411
ready to sell these people, and they really got a 
rip-off going on. And they got a piece out of the

13:04.431 --> 13:09.598
memorial where those apartments are right there, 
and then they had a piece... which is now an

13:10.743 --> 13:12.865
industrial park of the Woodlands. That was before 
we even conceded the Woodlands. Now, what year is

13:14.627 --> 13:15.728
this, roughly? That was about 61 or 62. And so I 
found out that the district judge in Conroe had

13:18.270 --> 13:28.801
some sort, or at least where the trust head 
department had to go, had a deal going on. So I

13:28.821 --> 13:34.346
threatened the bank with a lawsuit for her 
benefit, and that if I got it, I'd get a quarter of

13:28.821 --> 13:34.346
their profits. And therefore, this land was split 
up. The judge worked out a deal. that he would take

13:38.333 --> 13:46.125
part of Deer Conroe and let us have 500 acres on the 
edge of the well before he even didn't think it'd be

13:38.333 --> 13:46.125
part of the woods. Had nothing to do with the woods. 
For $49 an acre. And it had about a $50 acre of timber

13:50.471 --> 13:52.214
on it. So we were able to buy it that way. Now that is 
the first piece of real estate we had taken on. We

14:03.791 --> 14:04.813
had done some doing with some housing development 
with a person named Norman Dobbins back in 63, 64,

14:05.502 --> 14:17.655
doing a little housing development in several 
spots around the country, which we didn't make

14:05.502 --> 14:17.655
money. We lost money on that. This was strictly as 
an investment thing? Well, we were participating

14:21.239 --> 14:24.623
with him trying to help make it work. He was pretty 
good at design and creativity, but he was a very

14:24.703 --> 14:29.168
poor businessman. So we had to And we lost money on 
that, and we finally had to buy him out. But that

14:34.022 --> 14:35.263
wasn't very much money. We were just playing with 
it. We didn't do it. But about 62, 63, 64, then we had

14:38.367 --> 14:44.914
bought Pelican Island about in 62 or 63. We worked 
with A&M to take the A&M campus. We had looked at it.

14:50.741 --> 14:54.185
But then I got in real estate that way because we 
were using leverage and all of that. Pelican

14:55.667 --> 14:58.510
Island, I had a deal made buying it from, Mary 
Chapman Scott, they had about $10 million spent in

14:58.912 --> 15:01.995
it. And they had a big lawsuit with the city. I was 
able to solve the lawsuit, so I bought it for $1.8

15:04.057 --> 15:06.279
million. But I had a deal with Shell to sell 50 acres 
for about $1.6 million. So then I closed the deal. I

15:11.444 --> 15:11.824
sold it. And I had $200,000 or $300,000 left in 
Pelican Island. Then I promised to give A&M the

15:15.087 --> 15:22.454
acres they had, the 100 acres they had for the 
institute there. So then, of course, what got me

15:22.474 --> 15:27.619
into really the woodlands It was about that time, 
in 64, we'd have more oil. And this is all you had

15:30.671 --> 15:33.815
done, though, in terms of land and development? We 
knew in 62 that energy was in trouble. I knew in 62

15:39.020 --> 15:50.792
that that's when they opened the floodgates and 
all the Persian Gulf oil, Kuwait and Iran, and they

15:39.020 --> 15:50.792
were driving us up a wall and importing oil. And the 
price of oil was down to a quarter barrel. And I

15:53.996 --> 15:58.180
could foresee, and that Laubel Railroad 
Commission of Texas was only eight days for every

15:53.996 --> 15:58.180
oil well. So we concentrated on gas because we knew 
gas was going to be the future. So I concentrated

16:04.142 --> 16:05.684
all our effort on gas. And knowing that unless we 
did something else, we would probably be out of

16:06.825 --> 16:15.695
business because we could see oil was going to be in 
deep trouble as long as it continued flooding this

16:06.825 --> 16:15.695
country with cheap oil. But you were discovering, 
but you weren't trying to produce the gas. We were

16:18.237 --> 16:18.698
discovering. We were producing. Oh, yeah, we 
produced every foot we could get at $0.03 a

16:19.659 --> 16:22.502
thousand. The first gas contract I made was $0.03 a 
thousand at North Huron. And then it finally got up

16:27.860 --> 16:30.624
to six or eight cents. That was a pretty good price 
then. But we knew that gas was undervalued and we

16:32.548 --> 16:41.161
could make deals with major companies to drill gas 
properties easier than you could for oil

16:32.548 --> 16:41.161
properties. So I thought gas was the future from 
the standpoint of energy demand. And we

16:45.829 --> 16:48.173
concentrated 80% of everything related to gas. So 
we knew that. So then I started working on some of

16:50.977 --> 16:54.002
our, brokers they're out with all these brokers 
working for us you know 10 or 15 people they make it

16:55.096 --> 17:24.917
if they make a deal they make a dollar they don't 
make a deal with no money so they're starving to

16:55.096 --> 17:24.917
death so i said well if you find a piece of real 
estate up here you know where we can steal you know

16:55.096 --> 17:24.917
we'll may try to figure out how to leverage 
ourselves and buy it so when i had this piece of land

16:55.096 --> 17:24.917
that i bought from the judge and the bank here that i 
end up with that three or four acres out there i had

16:55.096 --> 17:24.917
this um person that um Max Newland, who was a 
forester up in that area, to cut the timber so we

17:25.184 --> 17:32.533
could get some money. So he cut the timber on that 
land, and I said, well, Max, if you know of a deal

17:33.914 --> 17:46.890
that we could put together, leverage-wise, and 
make a real good deal, because we don't have any

17:33.914 --> 17:46.890
money, we have to use leverage, see what you can put 
together. So he came in one day and he said, I'll

17:46.910 --> 17:52.677
tell you what, there's a 50,000-acre block up here 
called the Grogan, Cork, and Lumber Company. So

17:55.289 --> 17:56.431
that may be possible. And David Bentley, 
everybody had been trying to buy it for five years.

18:00.036 --> 18:02.239
And the problem was they had three family groups. 
They were down to cousins. The brothers had died

18:03.821 --> 18:05.043
off. They had a big lumber mill that had burned 
down, and they rebuilt it the same old-fashioned

18:05.924 --> 18:12.954
way, which was not efficient. They were in 
trouble. They had 80 heirs, some of them worth

18:15.077 --> 18:20.605
several hundred thousand dollars, couldn't 
afford a pack of cigarettes. And therefore, I

18:21.614 --> 18:24.217
said, all right, let me see if I can't put this 
together. So it took me two years and 62 or so to buy

18:24.318 --> 18:30.786
the Grogan-Cocker-Lummet coming. I had to settle 
those three lawsuits. I'm in three family groups

18:32.168 --> 18:33.970
fighting. And I bought it for $125.25 an acre, 
50,000 acres, of which only 4,000 were woodlands,

18:34.731 --> 18:41.640
and the rest were scattered in the county. And the 
reason that the way I figured the price, that I

18:42.762 --> 18:50.372
could sell the timber to Louisiana Pacific, and I 
had some minerals, So I figured the only thing I

18:50.858 --> 19:01.897
could afford to pay would be $125 an acre, or about 
$6 million for 50,000 acres, because I could pay

18:50.858 --> 19:01.897
the interest on the Louisiana timber contract and 
the minerals. And I got the Bank of Southwest at

19:02.979 --> 19:06.004
that time. Harold Vance used to be my professor at 
A&M, thought a lot of me. And he was able to say,

19:10.772 --> 19:16.782
okay, I'll make you a loan if you can get a release on 
the land, 20% release on the land, 15% payment. So I

19:17.318 --> 19:20.001
got the Grover and Cochran heirs to give me a 
release. Joe, you've probably never heard this

19:20.081 --> 19:21.242
story. I've never heard of it. Release of the land 
for paying 15%. And the bank gave me the money

19:26.767 --> 19:28.408
because I didn't have the money. So then I took the 
residual of the 50,000 acres and went to Great

19:29.049 --> 19:42.362
Southern about six months later and made a full $6 
