23:10.156 --> 23:16.002
Company deal. But we had the $50,000, I guess. So I 
then started. I had Carl Kamrath start in 66. What

23:25.353 --> 23:30.900
happened in the early 60s, 64, 65, we began to have 
these terrible riots. The Vietnam War was on.

23:33.515 --> 23:36.339
Bedford-Stuyvesant was having a riot up in New 
York City. Watts was having a riot. And I went to

23:37.982 --> 23:42.749
several of these YPO meetings to understand the 
plight of our cities. They're all in desperate

23:42.989 --> 23:44.111
shape. And what was happening in my reckoning, 
that what was destroying our cities was the

23:44.912 --> 23:57.851
proliferation of political subdivisions around 
the central core, and they can't manage it. And

23:57.871 --> 24:00.855
that there ought to be a better way to evolve an 
area. But why did you get in? That's sort of

24:02.774 --> 24:04.096
unusual. Here you are. Because the organization I 
belong to called Young Presidents Organization.

24:09.102 --> 24:09.423
Called what? Young Presidents Organization. 
Whenever we went anywhere, we didn't talk about

24:11.726 --> 24:15.371
business all the time. We talked about philosophy 
and humanities. And we exposed ourselves to the

24:18.515 --> 24:23.682
thoughts of really what makes a nation work. And 
these are local CEOs? Well, it's a national

24:25.424 --> 24:27.066
organization. It's a national organization. We 
have about 30 members here. And then, you see, at

24:29.219 --> 24:34.266
that time, our company was over worth more than a 
couple million dollars. So if you had over 50

24:34.286 --> 24:40.294
people or 100 people, you could qualify to be a 
young president before you're 40. You had to have a

24:40.314 --> 24:43.177
presidency before you're 40 years old or you don't 
qualify. So there were a lot of entrepreneurs.

24:46.402 --> 24:53.611
There were a lot of them that just inherited money, 
and they're usually duds, mad because they don't

24:46.402 --> 24:53.611
know what they did themselves or what their father 
did for them. So this was a hell of an organization.

24:56.915 --> 24:57.336
It really was. So therefore, I was exposed to 
really wanting what was destroying our cities.

25:03.572 --> 25:05.755
And then I got to thinking, well, why can't we do it 
better? And what other place would be better to do

25:06.977 --> 25:10.081
it than Houston? Because Houston was going to go to 
5 million people. I knew that. I knew they were the

25:13.547 --> 25:17.873
beauty, because I lived in Memorial by that time. I 
finished my house. I lived in Memorial from 58 on.

25:21.044 --> 25:24.149
When you came from service into Houston, you moved 
into Houston. You didn't stay in the office. Oh,

25:25.070 --> 25:26.472
no, I moved into Houston. I had an apartment my aunt 
had because there were no apartments available,

25:26.532 --> 25:30.238
and I ran that apartment house. Cynthia and I will 
never do it again. We had to scrape these plaster

25:32.160 --> 25:35.225
walls and paint the damn thing. I said, never again 
will I do that. She agreed with me, but then it was

25:37.328 --> 25:40.993
tough, and we had two kids and one other wife. So it 
was tough. It was tough for her. But then I was able

25:42.936 --> 25:45.800
to have a place to live here because my aunt was 
here. And then the... We first moved in with her

25:48.245 --> 25:56.513
mother, then I got the apartment, because I 
managed the apartment on Elgin, on Fannin and

25:48.245 --> 25:56.513
Elgin, that my aunt owned. So I was able to manage 
the apartment, because there was no housing

25:57.193 --> 26:01.437
available for a while. The first move was sent to 
his mother for about a month and a half, until I got

26:01.457 --> 26:07.243
the apartment, then we moved there, and then we had 
to redo it ourselves. But later on, I bought a

26:07.263 --> 26:13.288
house, so I started getting some royalties, so I 
ended up building a house. I had Ford, Powell &

26:14.409 --> 26:17.172
Carson design it from San Antonio, on North 
McGregor. Beautiful area. Ford, who did it? Ford?

26:23.550 --> 26:26.073
Ford Powell and Carson out of San Antonio. Neil 
Ford designed my house. Because I knew one of the

26:27.935 --> 26:32.040
architects that I was in the Army with, and he 
worked for Neil Ford at that time. Who was that? He

26:32.561 --> 26:33.562
was named Jerry Rogers. Okay. So Neil Ford 
designed my first house. It was only a six-down,

26:37.607 --> 26:39.149
beautiful house. Right on Timbercrest on North 
McGregor in a beautiful wooded area. But what

26:43.674 --> 26:47.158
happened, when the Supreme Court ruling came in, I 
knew it was going to go all black. So then I moved to

26:48.033 --> 26:52.520
Memorial into the Spring Branch School District, 
because I just wanted to go ahead. I guess we had

26:53.581 --> 26:57.927
seven, eight kids at that time, and we just wanted 
to be sure we got a good decent education here. So

26:58.668 --> 27:00.151
that's why I moved out to Memorial area. And then we 
built a house in 65, which we finished in 65, a big

27:00.271 --> 27:05.458
house up there. So anyway, by that time, I had gone 
around the country. It seemed I was destroying the

27:09.124 --> 27:11.147
nation, in my opinion. And how do you do it better? 
So this is what we got thinking. I asked Carl

27:17.058 --> 27:21.783
Cameron, I said, all right, Carl, and you pick, but 
you'll see their names in the book. How many acres

27:23.485 --> 27:27.129
would I need to build a town of 100,000? So they made 
that sketch. And that sketch is fairly accurate of

27:29.411 --> 27:31.974
what we did. So we moved before Pierre and Carl came 
out and they said, you need 20,000 acres. We only

27:38.721 --> 27:41.164
had 4,000 in that spot there. But see, I didn't 
think that was the right spot. looked at the 1960

27:44.564 --> 27:48.169
I-45 area, right where the corner was. 1960 I-45. I 
actually optioned 2,500 acres at $2,500, which I

27:50.912 --> 27:55.859
still have it now. But then I couldn't get the 
10,000 to 15,000 acres I need on the option, so I

27:56.900 --> 28:01.085
gave up on that sign. That was about in 67, 65, right 
after Carl finished his math. Then I said, well,

28:08.255 --> 28:11.499
the best place is, and we looked at where the 
airport was going to be. We knew where the freeway

28:11.519 --> 28:13.221
in the airport was going to be. I-45, and we knew 
where the airport was going to be. We looked at the

28:16.454 --> 28:20.260
sonic problem, because if you get too close to the 
airport, you destroy the chance. We looked at the

28:20.700 --> 28:21.982
freeway. We looked at the beauty of the woods. I had 
lived in Memorial. I knew the Memorial. In fact,

28:26.809 --> 28:38.284
one thing we found out by having this little pace at 
a home thing, that if we had a lot on the west side of

28:26.809 --> 28:38.284
town, and you had one with three trees and one with 
no trees, the one with three trees would get you

28:26.809 --> 28:38.284
$500 more. So we knew the value of the forest, the 
beauty. That's why Memorial is so popular. In

28:44.740 --> 28:50.906
1960, it was a hot thing at that time, but it's been 
screwed up by a bunch of small tracks. It's a big

28:51.567 --> 28:53.489
mess. It's like West Ham all over again. So we 
didn't want to do that. If you don't really design

28:58.514 --> 29:02.978
it properly, I didn't want to do it. So then we 
turned around and said, okay. Carl Cameron did his

29:05.060 --> 29:06.221
study. Then I started with Carl Charlie Lively to 
start building the block. It took 300

29:10.946 --> 29:12.908
transactions. to build a block. And you're trying 
to, you're going for 20,000 acres, or you're...

29:15.520 --> 29:21.127
Charles Lavery, I guess, you got all the data from 
him in the first quarter. Yeah. So then I had to

29:22.469 --> 29:24.913
build a block for 20,000 acres. And it was very 
difficult going with the Catholic Church and with

29:26.154 --> 29:36.989
the Celan Smith Foundation and with this fellow 
McCann at Waco Bank in Woodsville. Gee, what a

29:37.130 --> 29:38.832
terrible negotiation. Well, anyway, starting 
about in 1969, We heard about the University of

29:43.128 --> 29:45.892
Houston. We were building the block. We wanted to 
build a north campus and a south campus. So we went

29:49.938 --> 29:52.721
there, and they took them out before we'd ever done 
anything. And they agreed that they would like to

29:52.741 --> 29:56.346
have a site in the woodlands for the north campus. 
That was 68, 69. We've got some history about that

29:58.289 --> 30:01.253
in there. And then we retained. What I did then is I 
went out to Columbia. First, I had sent people,

30:06.521 --> 30:11.768
well, I went to Columbia first and decided to see 
what Rouse was doing. I looked at all the West Coast

30:16.737 --> 30:22.282
towns, Irvine, Westlake, Rancho Bernardo. But 
how did you get into that? I still don't

30:23.383 --> 30:24.183
understand. How you got into that new town, 
community planning concept? I knew that it was

30:28.247 --> 30:30.249
important for the nation. You see, Texas had 
unusual rule, extraterritorial jurisdiction.

30:35.833 --> 30:38.956
And I knew that if we're going to urbanize to five 
million people, you better do it right. You're

30:38.976 --> 30:41.198
going to destroy the area just like all these other 
cities. They're all in trouble. Detroit,

30:42.112 --> 30:44.695
Cleveland, you talk to them. They've got a central 
core and a hundred subdivisions that can't get

30:44.715 --> 30:49.921
along with each other. And they're destroyed. 
They can't manage. Unless you respond to the

30:52.483 --> 30:55.507
whole, you can't make it work. And that was the 
concept I had. That's what I sold HUD on. Had you

30:58.190 --> 31:03.155
done a lot of reading on this or meeting with people 
other than through the young residents? Well,

31:03.175 --> 31:05.017
naturally, no studying. When you see what caused 
it, you perceive what was wrong. I perceived what

31:09.723 --> 31:10.864
was wrong. with all the urbanization problems. 
And therefore, I felt that this could be a

31:13.740 --> 31:20.952
prototype, and it had flair as itself, of really 
what should be done. The woodlands are really

31:21.673 --> 31:24.598
unique in the country. There's nothing like it. 
And the people will realize it in about 10, 15

31:25.961 --> 31:28.004
years. All right, so then I went to Columbia, 
talked to Jim Rouse. I looked at Levittown, which

31:34.075 --> 31:36.058
is a mess. I looked at the, in fact, I went to the one 
at the Chicago. Well, it hadn't started yet. What?

31:42.614 --> 31:43.195
Park Forest. Yeah, Park Forest. It had started the 
old section, but it hadn't started the new HUD

31:44.096 --> 31:46.799
section. But I went all through. Westlake was the 
upper class. I went through

31:50.283 --> 31:56.029
Scotland and England and France. And all the new 
towns there are worker towns. All the ones on the

31:59.393 --> 32:02.397
west coast are upper class towns. Columbia, 
Maryland was the best I'd seen. The rest of

32:04.239 --> 32:07.142
Virginia was upper class. I'd looked at it, I'd 
seen all of them. So I thought what I did then, so I

32:09.804 --> 32:14.390
started hiring some of Rouse's people. Dick 
Brown, Mike Richman,

32:14.410 --> 32:19.977
Olen Ivins. I hired about 10 of them. So Rouse sent a 
man down threatening to sue me if I didn't quit

32:20.958 --> 32:26.265
hiring. Petito. So I said, okay, Jim, I won't hire 
anymore. And then we started building a team

32:29.789 --> 32:36.117
together because no one in this country had done 
anything of this magnitude of this like that we've

32:29.789 --> 32:36.117
talked of. We'd seen what they were doing. We'd 
watched the Kingwood thing was getting started by

32:38.559 --> 32:41.483
that time. We lost out on that. But no one did the 
amount of planning we did. We had social structure

32:46.329 --> 32:49.774
studies done by social artists. And that's one of 
the unusual things about all of this. Texas

32:51.997 --> 32:53.078
developers never did that. We had all the bishops 
together with me to plan the concept. Then we hired

32:56.643 --> 33:02.290
Ian McHarrig because he was the most important 
environmental planner in the world at that time,

32:56.643 --> 33:02.290
in my opinion. And where did you get into McHart, 
for example? Well, for an instant, Bob

33:05.943 --> 33:12.831
Hartsfield, who I had as my planning director at 
that time. And then where did Hartsfield come

33:13.251 --> 33:14.573
from? McHart was his instructor at the University 
of Pennsylvania. He said, before you decide who

33:19.959 --> 33:24.524
you're going to do your work, I want you to do one 
thing. I want you to read the book Design with

33:25.706 --> 33:28.209
Nature. Yeah, I remember seeing that reference, 
yeah. I did. So then I said, all right, MacArthur,

33:32.105 --> 33:35.328
would you come with us to do this project? And he 
said, well, he jumped at the chance, you see. And

33:38.971 --> 33:40.513
then I said, well, who want to do the master plan? He 
said he would do the environmental studies. And

33:42.695 --> 33:44.937
then the master plan, and I looked at all of them. I 
looked at two or three on the West Coast. Nobody in

33:46.639 --> 33:51.203
this part of the country had enough experience to 
do it, the type of master plan I wanted done. So I

33:51.223 --> 33:54.306
looked all over the country, and I found out that 
Pereira had done more. He had done more. He did

33:55.066 --> 33:55.807
Irvine. He did one in Iran at that time. He was doing 
that. I even talked to Doxiades, the Greek.

34:01.298 --> 34:02.199
planner at that time. But I couldn't feel I could 
come over here and be connected with him. But he had

34:05.824 --> 34:08.587
done some great work in all of Europe, you see. So 
then. But you'd given this an awful lot of, that's

34:10.470 --> 34:16.317
what amazes me about the whole, that you've cast 
your net worldwide already. Because if you want to

34:17.038 --> 34:28.573
make it something so different and so important, 
you had to really get the best talent or the best

34:17.038 --> 34:28.573
thought you could get anywhere and try to 
amalgamate into what we're talking about trying

34:17.038 --> 34:28.573
to put together. So then we had, oh man, we had 
meetings with the environmentalists. In other

34:32.304 --> 34:37.710
words, McCarrick came in before Prairie River 
started, and he brought ten scientists along with

34:32.304 --> 34:37.710
him. He usually retained them here. He had A&M. We 
did infrared, you know, photography on it. And we

34:42.295 --> 34:43.457
knew all the trees. We knew where to put the lines. 
We knew where to put the golf course and things like

34:44.378 --> 34:46.160
that. McCarrick with Rice did our drainage, which 
had been remarkably good. I'll tell you, Joe,

34:49.564 --> 34:55.190
earlier that we've had three big storms since when 
we had ten-inch rains. Yeah, almost had one this

34:55.390 --> 34:57.833
morning coming through. So we have done, and we did 
what to protect the wildlife, et cetera, et

34:58.387 --> 35:02.512
cetera. And we did that before you ever heard. We 
wrote the first environmental impact statement

35:03.733 --> 35:06.396
ever done by HUD. And they use it as a model for other 
projects like that. So this is what we did because

35:10.040 --> 35:18.891
McHarg spent one year on concern about the 
environment before we did any master planning

35:10.040 --> 35:18.891
that Prairie did. And then we put the plan together 
with McHarg. And surprisingly, it worked out well

35:21.534 --> 35:25.258
with Prairie and McHarg. We haven't changed too 
much conflict and how you preserve the trees, and

35:28.660 --> 35:31.604
how you preserve the wildlife, et cetera. All 
those things were thought of early on. And this is

35:34.328 --> 35:37.733
what no one had done before that time, and 
therefore. But then how do you urbanize, which is

35:38.134 --> 35:42.440
what's important that we got Houston to do? When we 
finally put all the block together, the full

35:44.583 --> 35:50.872
25,000, we've got some here maybe just five or six 
years ago, the last pieces. And we've got some now

35:51.213 --> 35:54.437
on the south side of the creek. We're trying to 
build a big lake. That'll be the next 10 years. How

35:59.525 --> 36:04.631
do you put this block together, but then how do you 
really be part of the whole? So Houston and Texas

36:04.671 --> 36:09.717
have a unique block called Exeterritory 
Jurisdiction. If the five-mile boundary from the

36:11.299 --> 36:28.941
city limits touched your land here, and it barely 
touched our southern boundary, then you can ask

36:11.299 --> 36:28.941
the city of Houston to take the whole 25,000 acres 
into their Exeterritory Jurisdiction, which

36:11.299 --> 36:28.941
means that no one can incorporate unless Houston 
approves it. Now, what that means is that as you

36:29.309 --> 36:36.760
urbanize, if we and I live there and Joe lives 
there, we don't make Houston work. We shouldn't be

36:38.202 --> 36:42.268
parasailing at the airport and the port and NASA 
and all that other stuff. We, those of us, because

36:42.288 --> 36:52.262
what was destroying all our towns in the country 
that I saw, the flight to the suburb of the town and

36:42.288 --> 36:52.262
the tax base was killing all the towns. And they'd 
get out in their little political subterfuge, and

36:53.153 --> 36:59.040
they could care less about New York City, et 
cetera. Or around Washington. They could care

37:01.263 --> 37:10.474
less about Washington, D.C. And that lack of 
carelessness and not being concerned is what's

37:01.263 --> 37:10.474
destroying all our cities. If your talent, and 
unfortunately the talent is mostly in the Anglo

37:11.255 --> 37:21.507
world at this time, until things happen as time 
goes on, that talent flees to the suburbs. It's

37:22.583 --> 37:23.705
going to destroy all your cities. The Woodlands 
can't do that. Those that have talent in the

37:27.089 --> 37:32.136
Woodlands, if I have any talent or Joe has any 
talent, may kind of make Houston work. Because

37:32.817 --> 37:35.080
Houston should never let that go. So this was part 
of your initial plan, is that what you did there is

37:35.360 --> 37:39.285
going to be part of the city. Now, let me say this. 
The people in the Woodlands don't like that. No,

37:42.830 --> 37:44.753
because that's not typical. They keep coming up a 
little bit. And the threat is, if you do this,

37:48.858 --> 37:52.303
Houston will make you prematurely, and you'll 
really get cut to pieces but you know that's the

37:52.537 --> 38:17.818
thing that that they would like to have what really 
what people want they don't want to live downtown

37:52.537 --> 38:17.818
in 610 loop some people will maybe four or five 
percent they want to want really particularly if

37:52.537 --> 38:17.818
you have any family the quality of urban life to be 
part of the whole that's what people want to be and

37:52.537 --> 38:17.818
that's the concept i have what they really want to 
be is part of the whole but have the quality of

38:18.608 --> 38:21.512
lifestyle that you may be left with. And then we 
build a job base. We worked on studies about the

38:23.495 --> 38:27.621
commercial side and the high-tech side. And we're 
going to someday make it going to be similar to

38:28.282 --> 38:33.189
Research Forest and part of the area there. I mean, 
Research Triangle. So that's a concept that's all

38:36.754 --> 38:39.117
coming together. That is very complex and very 
difficult to execute. You can see the trouble I had

38:43.183 --> 38:46.287
in the first 15 years is terrible. At what point did 
your concept of having an economically

38:46.992 --> 38:55.602
integrated community begin to develop? In other 
words, having the jobs there for the families

38:55.622 --> 38:58.306
to... Let me say this. The first exercise we did, we 
did a three-legged stool. Joe, you have that

39:03.552 --> 39:04.653
slide. We put on there that what urbanization 
should be is where you really have the

39:06.776 --> 39:14.485
